## MIE 522/622 

### Topics: Variable Selection Methods

Hitters data (Major League Baseball Data from the 1986 and 1987 seasons)

Info: https://rdrr.io/cran/ISLR/man/Hitters.html

#### **Goal**: to predict a baseball player’s Salary 

Salary = 1987 annual salary on opening day in thousands of dollars

Using variables associated with performance in the previous year (1986)

-   AtBat = Number of times at bat in 1986

-   Hits = Number of hits in 1986

-   HmRun = Number of home runs in 1986

-   Runs = Number of runs in 1986

-   RBI = Number of runs batted in in 1986

-   Walks = Number of walks in 1986

-   Years = Number of years in the major leagues

-   CAtBat = Number of times at bat during his career

-   CHits = Number of hits during his career

-   CHmRun = Number of home runs during his career

-   CRuns = Number of runs during his career

-   CRBI = Number of runs batted in during his career

-   CWalks = Number of walks during his career

Install Packages

```{r}
# Install Packages
install.packages("ISLR2")  
install.packages("leaps")  # for variable selection methods
```

Hitter data comes with ISLR2 package

```{r}
library(ISLR2)
Hitters <- Hitters
str(Hitters)
head(Hitters)
```

we see that Salary is missing for 59 players

```{r}
summary(Hitters)
sum(is.na(Hitters$Salary))
```

The na.omit() function removes all of the rows that have missing values in any variable

```{r}
# Lines 43
Hitters <- na.omit(Hitters) 
```

Starting with 322 players --\> 263 players included in the data who have a salary (Y) value documented in data

Best subset selection

```{r}
library(leaps)
```

regsubsets() function (which comes with leaps library) performs best subset methods

-   best subset selection --\> default

-   forward stepwise selection --\> Use the argument: method = "forward"

-   backward stepwise selection --\> Use the argument: method = "backward"

-   hybrid approach (forward and backward) --\> Use the argument: method = "seqrep"

Goal: to predict Y= Salary

```{r}
dim(Hitters)
```

There are 20-1= 19 potential independent variables

Let's first use Best Subset selection

```{r}
regfit.full <- regsubsets(Salary~ ., data = Hitters, nvmax = 19)
summary(regfit.full)
```

total of 2\^19 models created and compared In summary output: An asterisk indicates that an independent variable (shown in columns) is included in the corresponding model

-   e.g., best 1-variable model contains CRBI (Number of runs batted in during his career)

-   e.g., best 2-variable model contains CRBI and Hits (Number of hits in 1986)

We can examine one or more of goodness of fit metrics to select best overall model

```{r}
reg.summary <- summary(regfit.full)
names(reg.summary)
```

Adjusted R-squared of all best performing model sizes

```{r}
reg.summary$adjr2
which.max(reg.summary$adjr2)   # model with 11 independent variables performs the best when using adjusted r-squared as comparison metric
plot(reg.summary$adjr2 , xlab = " Number of Variables ", pch=16,type = "b",main = "Best Subset Selection Method",
     ylab = " Adjusted R-squared", col="purple") 
min(reg.summary$adjr2)
max(reg.summary$adjr2) 
```

Adjusted R2 increases from 34.8% (best one variable model) to 57.1% (best 11 variable model)

Plot RSS for best model selection

```{r}
plot(reg.summary$rss , xlab = " Number of Variables ", pch=16, main = "Best Subset Selection Method",
     ylab = "Residuals sum squared", type = "b", col="purple")
```

Final selected model with 11 variables:

```{r}
coef(regfit.full, 11)  # gives the model, independent variables and their coefficients
```

For example: What is the best model with 1,2,3,.. variables?

```{r}
coef(regfit.full, 1) 
coef(regfit.full, 2) 
coef(regfit.full, 3) 
```

#### Forward and Backward Stepwise Selection

**Forward stepwise selection**

```{r}
regfit.fwd <- regsubsets(Salary~ ., data = Hitters, nvmax = 19, method = "forward")
reg.summary2 <- summary(regfit.fwd)
which.max(reg.summary2$adjr2) # model with 11 independent variables selected
plot(reg.summary2$adjr2 , xlab = "Number of Variables ",ylab = " Adjusted R-squared", main = "Forward Selection Method", type = "b", pch=16, col="darkblue")
```

**Backward stepwise selection**

```{r}
regfit.bwd <- regsubsets(Salary~., data = Hitters, nvmax = 19, method = "backward")
reg.summary3 <- summary(regfit.bwd)
reg.summary3$adjr2
which.max(reg.summary3$adjr2) # model with 11 independent variables selected
plot(reg.summary3$adjr2 , xlab = "Number of Variables ",ylab = " Adjusted R-squared", main = "Backward Selection Method", type = "b", pch=16, col="darkred")
```

Compare final models with three approaches: Best subset, Forward stepwise, Backward stepeise --\> they selected the same final model

```{r}
coef(regfit.full, 11) 
coef(regfit.fwd, 11) 
coef(regfit.bwd, 11) 
coef(regfit.full, 7) 
coef(regfit.fwd, 7) 
coef(regfit.bwd, 7) 
```
